1 (d) The superintendent of public instruction shall ensure that
2 the Michigan merit examination meets all of the following:
3 (i) Is designed to test pupils on grade level content
4 expectations or course content expectations and this state's
5 content standards, as appropriate, in all subjects tested.
6 (ii) Complies with requirements of the no child left behind act
7 of 2001, Public Law 107-110, or the every student succeeds act,
8 Public Law 114-95, as applicable.
9 (iii) Is consistent with the code of fair testing practices in
10 education prepared by the joint committee Joint Committee on
11 testing practices Testing Practices of the American Psychological
12 Association.
13 (iv) Is factually accurate. If the superintendent of public
14 instruction determines that a question is not factually accurate
15 and should be excluded from scoring, the state board and the
16 superintendent of public instruction shall ensure that the question
17 is excluded from scoring.
18 (4) A school district or public school academy that operates a
19 high school shall include the number of school days a pupil was in
20 attendance at school each school year during high school and the
21 total number of school days in session for each of those school
22 years on each the pupil's high school transcript. all of the
23 following:
24 (a) For each high school graduate who has completed the
25 Michigan merit examination under this section, the pupil's scaled
26 score on each subject area component of the Michigan merit
27 examination.
28 (b) The number of school days the pupil was in attendance at
29 school each school year during high school and the total number of
