5
1 school days in session for each of those school years.
2 (5) The superintendent of public instruction shall work with
3 the provider or providers of the Michigan merit examination to
4 produce Michigan merit examination subject area scores for each
5 pupil participating in the Michigan merit examination. , including
6 scaling and merging of test items for the different subject area
7 components. To the extent that the department determines that
8 additional test items beyond those included in the college entrance
9 component of the Michigan merit examination are required in a
10 particular subject area, the department shall ensure that all test
11 items in that subject area are scaled and merged for the purposes
12 of producing a Michigan merit examination subject area score. The
13 superintendent of public instruction shall design and distribute to
14 school districts, public school academies, intermediate school
15 districts, and nonpublic schools a simple and concise document that
16 describes the scoring for each subject area and indicates the
17 scaled score ranges for each subject area.
18 (6) The Michigan merit examination shall must be administered
19 each year after March 1 and before June 1 to pupils in grade 11. in
20 each school district and public school academy during the last 12
21 weeks of the school district's or public school academy's school
22 year. The superintendent of public instruction shall ensure that
23 the Michigan merit examination is scored and the scores are
24 returned to pupils, their pupils' parents or legal guardians, and
25 schools not later than the beginning of the pupil's first semester
26 of grade 12. The returned scores shall must indicate at least the
27 pupil's scaled score for each subject area component and the range
28 of scaled scores for each subject area. In reporting the scores to
29 pupils, parents or legal guardians, and schools, the superintendent
CRM H02513'25 (H-2) 2du50s

6
1 of public instruction shall provide standards-specific, meaningful,
2 and timely feedback on the pupil's performance on the Michigan
3 merit examination.
4 (7) A school district or public school academy shall
5 administer the complete Michigan merit examination to a pupil only
6 once and shall not administer the complete Michigan merit
7 examination to the same pupil more than once. If a pupil does not
8 take the complete Michigan merit examination in grade 11, the
9 school district or public school academy shall administer the
10 complete Michigan merit examination to the pupil in grade 12. If a
11 pupil chooses to retake the college entrance examination component
12 of the Michigan merit examination, as described in subsection
13 (2)(a), the pupil may do so through the provider of the college
14 entrance examination component and the cost of the retake is the
15 responsibility of the pupil unless all of the following are met:
16 (a) The pupil has taken the complete Michigan merit
17 examination.
18 (b) The pupil meets the income eligibility criteria for free
19 breakfast, lunch, or milk, as determined under the Richard B.
20 Russell national school lunch act, 42 USC 1751 to 1769j.
21 (c) The pupil has applied to the provider of the college
22 entrance examination component for a scholarship or fee waiver to
23 cover the cost of the retake and that application has been denied.
24 (d) After taking the complete Michigan merit examination, the
25 pupil has not already received a free retake of the college
26 entrance examination component paid for either by this state or
27 through a scholarship or fee waiver by the provider.
28 (8) The superintendent of public instruction shall ensure that
29 the length of the Michigan merit examination and the combined total
