7
1 time necessary to administer all of the components of the Michigan
2 merit examination are the shortest possible that will still
3 maintain the degree of reliability and validity of the Michigan
4 merit examination results determined necessary by the
5 superintendent of public instruction. The superintendent of public
6 instruction shall ensure that the maximum total combined length of
7 time that schools are required to set aside for pupils to answer
8 all test questions on the Michigan merit examination does not
9 exceed 8 hours if the superintendent of public instruction
10 determines that sufficient alignment to with applicable Michigan
11 merit curriculum content standards can be achieved within that time
12 limit.
13 (9) A school district or public school academy shall provide
14 accommodations to a pupil with disabilities for the Michigan merit
15 examination, as provided under section 504 of title V of the
16 rehabilitation act of 1973, 29 USC 794; subtitle part A of title
17 subchapter II of the Americans with disabilities act of 1990, 42
18 USC 12131 to 12134; the individuals with disabilities education act
19 amendments of 1997, Public Law 105-17; and the implementing
20 regulations for those statutes. The provider or providers of the
21 Michigan merit examination and the superintendent of public
22 instruction shall mutually agree upon on the accommodations to be
23 provided under this subsection.
24 (10) To the greatest extent possible, the Michigan merit
25 examination shall must be based on grade level content expectations
26 or course content expectations and this state's content standards,
27 as appropriate. Not later than July 1, 2008, the department shall
28 identify specific grade level content expectations to be taught
29 before and after the middle of grade 11, so that teachers will know
