3 (12) (13) The purpose of the Michigan merit examination is to
4 assess pupil performance in mathematics, science, social studies,
5 and English language arts for the purpose of improving academic
6 achievement and establishing a statewide standard of competency.
7 The assessment under this section provides a common measure of data
8 that will contribute to the improvement of Michigan schools'
9 curriculum and instruction by encouraging alignment with Michigan's
10 curriculum framework standards and promotes pupil participation in
11 higher level mathematics, science, social studies, and English
12 language arts courses. These standards are based upon on the
13 expectations of what pupils should learn through high school and
14 are aligned with national standards.
15 (13) (14) In addition to the other requirements of this
16 section and the requirements of 1970 PA 38, MCL 388.1081 to
17 388.1086, beginning with assessments conducted during the 2016-2017
18 school year, the superintendent of public instruction shall ensure
19 that the Michigan merit examination social studies component and
20 the M-STEP and any successor state assessment for social studies,
21 as appropriate, include questions related to the learning
22 objectives in the state board recommended model core academic
23 curriculum standards concerning genocide, including, but not
24 limited to, the Holocaust and the Armenian Genocide.
25 (14) For a pupil enrolled in a middle college program, other
26 than a middle college operated as a shared educational entity or a
27 specialized shared educational entity, if the pupil receives at
28 least 50% of the pupil's instruction at the high school while in
29 grade 11, the Michigan merit examination must be administered to
CRM H02513'25 (H-2) 2du50s

